\begin_inset Formula $\Y_{(i)j}=\mubf+\betabf_{(i)}+\varepsilonbf_{(i)j},\;\; i=1,\,\cdots,\, p,\;\; j=1,\,\cdots,\, n_{(i)}$
\end_inset

.
 We use the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $(i)$
\end_inset

 to represent the ith group, and we 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 without the parenthesis to represent the jth observation.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Y_{(i)j}\in\real{r}$
\end_inset

 is the jth observation in the ith group, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{(i)}$
\end_inset

 is the number of observations in the ith group, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mubf\in\real{r}$
\end_inset

 is the grand mean, 
\begin_inset Formula $\betabf_{(i)}\in\real{r}$
\end_inset

